<subSubSection id="EC13896615AFE748B88FF6480F840257" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="597B6B4DF09C8B9366EA3985D083BF49" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Distribution</paragraph>
<paragraph id="5D234B1E7B6F064018C878661B7CD274" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
The typical form is only known from the Mountain Province in northern Luzon (
<bibRefCitation id="FB34BB477C31B3BAC639B87286A72A34" author="Hecher, C." journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="435 - 456" refId="B5979245" refString="Hecher, C., 2006. Review of the genus Pseudovelia (Heteroptera, Veliidae) on the Philippines: Part II: Greater Luzon. Denisia 19: 435 - 456" title="Review of the genus Pseudovelia (Heteroptera, Veliidae) on the Philippines: Part II: Greater Luzon" volume="19" year="2006">Hecher 2006</bibRefCitation>
). See Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B17DADE5095CC43AC256BAD9E211CC30" captionStart="Figure 7" captionStartId="F5979098" captionText="Figure 7. Distribution of the collecting sites of Gerromorpha material (part 1) treated in this study." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure7" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467247" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">7</figureCitation>
for the collecting sites of the slightly varying Mindoro material.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="78D9F0CDBCD08DEEA6C86F5BBF0FFC2D" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="F6A0686633A401FAC73CB6C919C6EBCA" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8AFD4AB3F0D83CE694BE23253B0DB95F" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">
The specimens (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F1399F379B610020A5225AA9AF2B6D47" captionStart="Figure 6" captionStartId="F5979094" captionText="Figure 6. Selected habitus illustrations of Gerromorpha of Mindoro A. Hebrus sp.; B. Mesovelia vittigera; C. Hydrometra mindoroensis; D. Microvelia douglasi; E. Pseudovelia cf. curvata; F. Strongylovelia mindoroensis; G. Rhagovelia mindoroensis; H. Rhagovelia raddai. Scale bars 1 mm." figureDoi="10.3897/BDJ.8.e56883.figure6" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/467166" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">6</figureCitation>
E) closely resemble those of 
<taxonomicName id="6A1A88A002E2938466BD5B8998CBDE5A" authorityName="Hecher" authorityYear="2006" class="Insecta" family="Veliidae" genus="Pseudovelia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Pseudovelia curvata" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="curvata">
<emphasis id="F74473AC7A2A1F91A6F962507C287632" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Pseudovelia curvata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hecher, 2006 following the key in 
<bibRefCitation id="52913E6CF2DA5BD97DAB5C646483F6F7" author="Hecher, C." journalOrPublisher="Denisia" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" pagination="435 - 456" refId="B5979245" refString="Hecher, C., 2006. Review of the genus Pseudovelia (Heteroptera, Veliidae) on the Philippines: Part II: Greater Luzon. Denisia 19: 435 - 456" title="Review of the genus Pseudovelia (Heteroptera, Veliidae) on the Philippines: Part II: Greater Luzon" volume="19" year="2006">Hecher (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, displaying the following characters: first metatarsal segment devoid of a tuft of very long setae basally; first and second metatarsal segment with a row of long setae over entire length; and metatarsus about half as long as metatibia. However, the pygophore of males has long, bristle-like setae on its caudo-lateral margin like 
<taxonomicName id="981293A37106708357FED9975D3A02E9" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Aphididae" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. gapudi" order="Hemiptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gapudi">
<emphasis id="4223826B996F60EBB15056F2034C7AF7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">P. gapudi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Hecher, 2006. Given the lack of any records, except for the specimens in hand and the type material from northern Luzon, it must remain unsolved if the material is conspecific or represents a new, but related species. This variation is only recognised in our specimens from Mindoro.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="B064AED0962BFA8FB40190CE71096BCE" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883" type="habitat">
<paragraph id="BD84E21E8E179FB7669F404F5659413C" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">Habitat</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1ADEFB9AAA1FCF0A4FC2EE2FC15B17D5" pageId="0" pageNumber="56883">The specimens were found at banks of creeks and rivers, both in calm and flowing sections.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
